Selling Cycle -


| Step                  | Real-Life Example                                                                                                                                    |
| --------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Le.**               | A school principal calls your company asking, â€œDo you sell computers for labs?â€ You record this person as a lead.                                    |
| **Opp.**              | You talk to them more and find out they want 20 computers next month. You create an opportunity â€” the deal has a good chance of happening.           |
| **Quo.**              | The principal asks for prices. You make a quotation â€” it includes items, price, tax, and delivery time. You email it to them.                        |
| **Bl. Ord. (opt.)**   | The school says, â€œWeâ€™ll buy 100 computers this year but order 20 each month.â€ You create a blanket order to fix the long-term agreement.             |
| **SO**                | After a few days, the school confirms: â€œYes, send 20 computers as per quotation.â€ You convert the quotation to a sales order. Stock is now reserved. |
| **Pay. (Adv.)**       | The school pays 50% in advance. You record this as an advance payment entry linked to the sales order.                                               |
| **DN**                | Your warehouse packs and sends 20 computers to the school. You create a delivery note â€” stock quantity reduces automatically.                        |
| **Pack. Slip (opt.)** | Your logistics team prints a packing slip that lists whatâ€™s inside each box â€” useful for large shipments.                                            |
| **SI**                | Once items are delivered, you create a sales invoice â€” the legal document asking for remaining payment.                                              |
| **Pay. (Final)**      | The school pays the remaining 50%. You record this as a payment entry. The invoice is marked as paid.                                                |


